Review: The original filter from my Dyson vacuum met an unfortunate fate – it was snatched by the neighbor's dog! I had taken it out for cleaning and left it on the front porch table to dry. Regrettably, the neighbor's dog got to it just before I could retrieve it, prompting me to seek a replacement. Since the Dyson-branded ones were too pricey, I stumbled upon these off-brand alternatives and decided to give them a shot; especially since they offered three replacements at a budget-friendly price.The quality of these off-brand filters pleasantly surprised me. They fit perfectly and exhibit a robust build similar to Dyson's. However, I did notice that the part of the filter with the faucet marking felt a bit stiff and thinner than Dyson. In terms of performance, they seem to be doing a commendable job, delivering excellent suction when using the vacuum.One noticeable difference is that these off-brand filters tend to accumulate dirt faster than the original Dyson ones. I find myself needing to clean them sooner than I would with the Dyson brand. The upside is that they are significantly easier and quicker to clean, probably because the dirt appears to be primarily on the surface, allowing for swift rinsing. In contrast, the original Dyson filter often requires more thorough cleaning, as it seems to trap dirt within its material.Despite the need for more frequent cleaning and replacements, having three spare filters is a definite advantage. It means I don't have to wait for one to dry before using the vacuum again, ensuring continuous cleaning convenience.

Description: Cuisinart Electric Knife with Cutting Board, Stainless Steel/Black, CEK-41
Cuisinart Electric Knife with Cutting Board, Stainless Steel/Black, CEK-41
Review: Pros: Easily cuts through almost anything. Easy to clean blades.Cons: Holding down the "On" button gets a bit tiresome.I'm not sure why it took me so long to purchase an electric knife. My mother used to use one and it seemed so old fashioned and unnecessary. Not too long ago, as I was struggling, trying to carve a large roast, the vision of an electric knife came to me. I'm very glad I bought one.This is a relatively simple electric knife. It only has one set of blades. It has an electric cord. It has a button on top that you depress when you want the knife to start working.The "knife" is composed of two very sharp serrated blades that hook together. When the knife is turned on (when the top button is depressed and held) the two blades start moving in opposite directions. Meat is cut with a sawing motion of the blades.The cut is quick and smooth. You can diagonally slice flank steak into thin, professional looking slices. You can cut through bone, sinew, thick cuts.The blades are removable and easy to wash. The knife handle is heavy plastic and must be cleaned with a damp cloth.I purposely selected a knife that had an electric cord. One does have to take care to ensure the cord is out of the way when slicing. I don't use an electric knife often enough to keep a rechargeable one charged and ready to go when I need it.Also, this knife does not come with a storage box or container. The knives fit into a plastic safety sleeve and I keep everything in the cardboard box it came in.My only gripe is that holding the large On button down while slicing a large cut of meat can get tiresome on my thumb. It's not as tiresome as using a carving knife, however, if you are doing a lot of carving, you will need to keep up the thumb pressure to keep the knife working.

Description: Cuisinart Electric Knife with Cutting Board, Stainless Steel/Black, CEK-41
Cuisinart Electric Knife with Cutting Board, Stainless Steel/Black, CEK-41
Review: Compared to other electric knives I've tried; this one is the best and deserves 5 stars but there are a few improvements I would make.  I use this knife to routinely slice up large turkey breasts.Pros:  * Great power.  * The blades are perfectly flush together, as they should be.Opportunities to improve:  * The grip circumference is really large.  Perhaps this is necessary to accommodate the powerful motor and gearing, but it makes holding and using the knife harder on the hand and forearm.  Maybe not an issue for people with large hands  * I would prefer as offset blade option.  Because the grip circumference is so large, maneuvering the knife down all the way through the meat and to the cutting board is awkward.  Offset blades would make it much easier.

Wevac Vacuum Sealer Bags 8x50, 11x50 Rolls 2 pack for Food Saver, Seal a Meal, Weston. Commercial Grade, BPA Free, Heavy Duty, Great for vac storage, Meal Prep or Sous Vide
Review: I recently purchased these vacuum seal bags to use with my FoodSaver vacuum sealer, and I am thoroughly impressed with their performance. Here are some key points from my experience:Performance: These bags work flawlessly with my FoodSaver vacuum sealer. The sealing process is just as efficient as with the original FoodSaver bags. Every seal has been airtight, keeping my food fresh for much longer. I haven’t experienced any issues with leaks or compromised seals.Size and Quality Perfect. The size of these bags is exactly the same as the original FoodSaver bags, making them a convenient replacement. One notable difference is that the roll of these bags is thicker than the original FoodSaver rolls. This is because you get more bags in each roll, which is great for long-term use.Due to the thicker roll, it doesn’t fit into the FoodSaver storage area initially. However, once you use enough of the roll, it will fit perfectly into the designated storage area of the vacuum sealer.Overall, I highly recommend these vacuum seal bags for anyone looking to save money without sacrificing quality. They provide excellent performance and durability, and the only minor inconvenience is the initial fit in the storage area. Once you get past that, they are just as good as the original bags that came with the FoodSaver sealer. Great value for the price!

Review: I am new to vacuum sealers and bags but I got a very affordable vac sealer and unknown to me they sell products like this ehere you can basically customize a bag to whatever size you want within the width obviously. I am glad I went the roll route vs premade sized bags.This maybe obvious to some but each time you want to make a new bag you have to seal the end then cut to size and seal again.  On smaller items i was curious if I would cut the 11" width in half and make a perpendicular seal to make a smaller bag and yah duh it obviously works so that IMO makes it even more versatile.All in all the bags work well with my sealer and I think the rolled is a more versatile method.Theoretically I don't know if they make bags the length of a full rack of ribs but i could cut the roll to that size and have it fit.  Great buy and ohh yeah the included for some reason a large bag for like blankets etc that you use a ship vac type connector which was a cool freebie bonus.

Review: These rolls work great for creating custom size bag for vacuum sealing. Economical and easy to use. The textured surface is great for marking the bag with a Sharpie. One tip for those with a FoodSaver, the rolls will not fit in the machine as shipped, they are too large in diameter. Save the tubes from your old rolls and transfer half the roll to the old tube. Takes about 5-10 min. Go slow and make sure you keep the ends tidy and even. Half a roll fits fine. It is a bit of work but the cost savings are great as the overall cost is about one third that of the FoodSaver brand (per foot on the 11"x50 (2 rolls of 50') package}
